# LHTL Week 2: Chunking

## [What is a Chunk?]

* What is 'chunking'?
* What is a 'chunk'?
* What is happening in your brain when you are attempting to chunk?
* Does this process use the focused or diffuse mode of thinking and why?

## [How to form a Chunk]

* How are chunks formed in the context of, for example, learning a song on the guitar?
* Are chunks a fixed size?
* What are the 3 steps of chunking?
* What role does understanding play in chunking? Are they the same thing?
* What are the top-down and bottom-up chunking processes, and what do we call their intersection?

## [Illusions of Competence]

* What are "illusions of competence" in regard to learning?
* Is re-reading an effective study method? What is a better alternative?
* How many of the 'slots' in working memory does one chunk take up? How does this behaviour benefit the learning process?
* If you look at a solution and understand why it is correct, does that mean that you understand the material fully, and could solve a similar problem on your own?
* Is a desire to learn and a lot of time spent with the material a guarantee that you'll actually learn it?
* What value do mistakes have in the learning process?
* How does recalling material in different contexts affect the learning process and why?

## [Retrieval Practice]

* What is "retrieval practice"?
* How can you integrate a flashcard retrieval practice system into your studies? (See [idorecall.com] or [web.ankiapp.com]).

## What Motivates You?

* Why is it easier to learn when you find the material interesting?
* Look up [brainfacts.org] for more information about your brain.

## [The Value of a Library of Chunks]

* How does having a larger "library" of chunks available to you affect your ability to solve problems in a particular area? Why is this?

